INSERT INTO `periodicelements` VALUES (1,'H','Hydrogen',1.008,1,1,'s','Nonmetal','Gas',0.00008988,13.99,20.271,'1s1',2.2,'+1, -1','Colorless gas','Henry Cavendish',1766,0,'Hydrogen is the lightest and most abundant element in the universe, accounting for roughly 75% of its elemental mass. Discovered by Henry Cavendish in 1766, hydrogen plays a vital role in the structure of the universe, especially in stars, where it undergoes nuclear fusion to release energy. In its diatomic form (H?), it is a colorless, odorless, tasteless gas that is highly flammable, famously involved in the Hindenburg disaster. It is used in fuel cells, ammonia production, and hydrogenation. Despite being simple in structure, it?s critical in chemistry and biology, being part of water and organic compounds. Its unique bonding properties make it a cornerstone of life and chemical science.'),(2,'He','Helium',4.0026,1,18,'s','Noble Gas','Gas',0.0001786,NULL,4.222,'1s2',NULL,'0','Colorless gas','Pierre Janssen',1868,0,'Helium was first discovered in the solar spectrum in 1868 during a solar eclipse before being found on Earth. As the second lightest and second most abundant element in the universe, it is a key product of nuclear fusion in stars. It is inert, non-toxic, non-flammable, and colorless. Helium is used in balloons, deep-sea breathing systems, and cryogenics due to its low boiling point. It does not solidify at standard pressure, even near absolute zero. Because it is chemically inert, helium has no known stable compounds at normal conditions. It?s also used to cool superconducting magnets in MRI machines and particle accelerators.'),(3,'Li','Lithium',6.94,2,1,'s','Alkali Metal','Solid',0.534,453.69,1603,'[He] 2s1',0.98,'+1','Silvery-white','Johan August Arfvedson',1817,0,'Lithium is the lightest solid element and a member of the alkali metal group. Discovered by Johan August Arfvedson in 1817, it is a soft, silver-white metal that reacts rapidly with water and air. Lithium is highly valuable in modern technology, primarily for its use in rechargeable lithium-ion batteries that power everything from smartphones to electric vehicles. It also has applications in ceramics, glass production, and as a mood-stabilizing drug for treating bipolar disorder. Despite being rare in Earth?s crust, lithium is essential in energy storage and the transition to cleaner technologies. It?s often extracted from brine pools and mineral ores.'),(4,'Be','Beryllium',9.0122,2,2,'s','Alkaline Earth Metal','Solid',1.85,1560,2742,'[He] 2s2',1.57,'+2','White-gray metallic','Louis Nicolas Vauquelin',1798,0,'Beryllium is a rare, hard, grayish metal that belongs to the alkaline earth metals. Discovered by Louis Nicolas Vauquelin in 1798, it was first isolated in 1828. Despite its lightweight, it is remarkably stiff and has a high melting point. These properties make beryllium ideal for aerospace applications, including satellites and aircraft components. It is also used in nuclear reactors as a neutron reflector and moderator. However, beryllium is toxic when inhaled, and exposure must be carefully controlled. Its transparent oxide is used in X-ray windows, and it has a high thermal conductivity, making it valuable in electronics as well.'),(5,'B','Boron',10.81,2,13,'p','Metalloid','Solid',2.34,2349,4200,'[He] 2s2 2p1',2.04,'+3','Black-brown','Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac',1808,0,'Boron is a metalloid element that plays an essential role in both industrial and biological systems. Discovered in 1808 by Gay-Lussac and Thenard, it exists as a brittle black-brown solid at room temperature. Boron compounds are vital in the manufacture of borosilicate glass, ceramics, and fiberglass. In agriculture, boron is an important micronutrient for plants. It?s also a component in laundry detergents and used in neutron-absorbing control rods in nuclear reactors. Boron?s unusual bonding abilities allow it to form complex molecules, and researchers continue to explore its potential in nanotechnology and medicine.'),(6,'C','Carbon',12.011,2,14,'p','Nonmetal','Solid',2.267,3823,4300,'[He] 2s2 2p2',2.55,'+4, +2, -4','Black (graphite), transparent (diamond)','Known since ancient times',NULL,0,'Carbon is the fourth most abundant element in the universe and the cornerstone of organic chemistry. It forms a vast number of compounds, more than any other element. Found in all known life forms, carbon can bond with itself and many other elements in chains and rings. Its allotropes include diamond, graphite, and graphene, each with unique properties?diamond is extremely hard, while graphite conducts electricity. Carbon?s role extends from biological molecules to energy sources like coal and petroleum. It is also central in climate science due to its presence in carbon dioxide, a major greenhouse gas.'),(7,'N','Nitrogen',14.007,2,15,'p','Nonmetal','Gas',0.0012506,63.15,77.36,'[He] 2s2 2p3',3.04,'-3, +3, +5','Colorless gas','Daniel Rutherford',1772,0,'Nitrogen makes up about 78% of Earth?s atmosphere and is a key component of proteins and nucleic acids in all living organisms. Discovered by Daniel Rutherford in 1772, nitrogen is inert in its diatomic form (N?) and doesn?t easily react under normal conditions. However, when combined in compounds like ammonia or nitrates, it becomes biologically and chemically active. Nitrogen is essential in fertilizers and plays a significant role in the nitrogen cycle. It is also used in cryogenics, food preservation, and as a protective atmosphere in electronics manufacturing. Liquid nitrogen is commonly used in scientific and medical settings for rapid cooling.'),(8,'O','Oxygen',15.999,2,16,'p','Nonmetal','Gas',0.001429,54.36,90.2,'[He] 2s2 2p4',3.44,'-2','Colorless gas','Carl Wilhelm Scheele',1774,0,'Oxygen is the most abundant element in Earth?s crust and the third most abundant in the universe. Discovered independently by Carl Wilhelm Scheele and Joseph Priestley in the 1770s, it is vital for respiration in most life forms and combustion processes. Diatomic oxygen (O?) constitutes 21% of Earth?s atmosphere. It?s also found in water (H?O), rocks, and many organic compounds. Oxygen supports life, fire, and various industrial processes such as steel production and wastewater treatment. In its ozone (O?) form, it shields Earth from harmful UV radiation. Oxygen is essential to both biology and chemistry.'),(9,'F','Fluorine',18.998,2,17,'p','Halogen','Gas',0.001696,53.53,85.03,'[He] 2s2 2p5',3.98,'-1','Pale yellow gas','Henri Moissan',1886,0,'Fluorine is the most electronegative and reactive of all elements, discovered by Henri Moissan in 1886 after years of hazardous experiments. It is a pale yellow gas at room temperature and can form compounds with almost all other elements. Fluorine is used in toothpaste to help prevent dental cavities and in the production of Teflon for non-stick cookware. Its compounds are crucial in nuclear fuel processing and even in medical imaging. Due to its extreme reactivity, fluorine must be handled with great care, and it plays a major role in both everyday consumer goods and advanced technologies.'),(10,'Ne','Neon',20.18,2,18,'p','Noble Gas','Gas',0.0008999,24.56,27.07,'[He] 2s2 2p6',NULL,'0','Colorless gas','William Ramsay',1898,0,'Neon is a noble gas discovered by William Ramsay and Morris Travers in 1898. It is colorless, odorless, and inert under most conditions. Neon is best known for its bright red-orange glow in neon signs, which became iconic in advertising and nightlife. It is used in high-voltage indicators, vacuum tubes, and cryogenics. Although rare in Earth?s atmosphere, it is relatively abundant in the universe, especially in stars. Its name comes from the Greek ?neos,? meaning new. Despite its low chemical reactivity, neon has a major cultural and technological presence thanks to its visual appeal in lighting applications.'),(11,'Na','Sodium',22.99,3,1,'s','Alkali Metal','Solid',0.971,370.87,1156,'[Ne] 3s1',0.93,'+1','Silvery-white metallic','Humphry Davy',1807,0,'Sodium is a soft, silvery-white metal and a member of the alkali metals group. Discovered by Humphry Davy in 1807, sodium is highly reactive, especially with water, producing hydrogen gas and heat. It is never found in nature in its pure form but is abundant in compounds like table salt (sodium chloride). Sodium plays essential roles in biology, especially in nerve transmission and fluid balance in animals. In industry, sodium is used in the production of glass, soap, and paper. It?s also used as a coolant in some types of nuclear reactors. Due to its reactivity, sodium is stored under oil.'),(12,'Mg','Magnesium',24.305,3,2,'s','Alkaline Earth Metal','Solid',1.738,923,1363,'[Ne] 3s2',1.31,'+2','Shiny gray solid','Joseph Black',1755,0,'Magnesium is a lightweight metal that burns with an intense white flame, making it ideal for fireworks and flares. Discovered in 1755 by Joseph Black, magnesium is abundant in Earth?s crust and is found in minerals like dolomite and magnesite. It plays a critical role in biology, especially in chlorophyll and over 300 enzymatic reactions in the human body. Magnesium alloys are used in aircraft and automotive manufacturing due to their light weight and strength. Its presence in Epsom salts provides therapeutic benefits. Despite its flammability in powder form, solid magnesium is relatively stable in air.'),(13,'Al','Aluminum',26.982,3,13,'p','Post-transition Metal','Solid',2.7,933.47,2792,'[Ne] 3s2 3p1',1.61,'+3','Silvery-white','Hans Christian Ørsted',1825,0,'Aluminum is the most abundant metal in Earth?s crust and is known for its lightweight, non-corrosive properties. Discovered in 1825 by Hans Christian Ørsted, it was once considered more valuable than gold. Today, it is used in a wide range of products, including aircraft, automobiles, food packaging, and household foil. Aluminum forms a protective oxide layer that prevents corrosion. It is also recyclable without loss of quality, making it environmentally important. Despite being reactive, it is found only in compounds like bauxite. Its low density and strength make it indispensable in modern engineering and architecture.'),(14,'Si','Silicon',28.085,3,14,'p','Metalloid','Solid',2.329,1687,3538,'[Ne] 3s2 3p2',1.9,'+4, -4','Dark gray with metallic luster','Jöns Jacob Berzelius',1823,0,'Silicon is a metalloid that bridges the properties of metals and nonmetals. Discovered in 1823 by Jöns Jacob Berzelius, it is the second most abundant element in Earth?s crust. Silicon is crucial in electronics as the primary material used in semiconductors and computer chips. It also forms the backbone of minerals such as quartz and sand, which are used in construction materials like glass and concrete. Silicon does not occur naturally in its pure form but is widely used in both industrial and biological systems. Its unique electrical properties have made it the foundation of the modern digital age.'),(15,'P','Phosphorus',30.974,3,15,'p','Nonmetal','Solid',1.823,317.3,553.7,'[Ne] 3s2 3p3',2.19,'-3, +3, +5','White, red, or black','Hennig Brand',1669,0,'Phosphorus was discovered in 1669 by Hennig Brand while experimenting with urine in search of gold. It exists in several allotropes, including white, red, and black phosphorus, each with different properties. White phosphorus is highly reactive and glows in the dark, while red phosphorus is more stable and used in safety matches. Phosphorus is essential to life, forming part of DNA, RNA, and ATP, the energy currency of cells. It is a key component of fertilizers, detergents, and pesticides. However, excessive phosphorus in water bodies leads to eutrophication, harming aquatic ecosystems.'),(16,'S','Sulfur',32.06,3,16,'p','Nonmetal','Solid',2.07,388.36,717.87,'[Ne] 3s2 3p4',2.58,'-2, +4, +6','Bright yellow crystalline solid','Known since ancient times',NULL,0,'Sulfur is a bright yellow, brittle nonmetal that has been known since ancient times. It is found near hot springs, volcanoes, and in many minerals. Sulfur is essential to life and is present in amino acids, vitamins, and enzymes. It is also widely used in industry for the production of sulfuric acid, fertilizers, and rubber vulcanization. Sulfur burns with a blue flame and produces a distinctive rotten-egg smell when in compound form. It plays a vital role in climate regulation through volcanic emissions and atmospheric chemistry. In nature, sulfur cycles between the land, air, and water in various chemical forms.'),(17,'Cl','Chlorine',35.45,3,17,'p','Halogen','Gas',0.003214,171.6,239.11,'[Ne] 3s2 3p5',3.16,'-1, +1, +5, +7','Yellow-green gas','Carl Wilhelm Scheele',1774,0,'Chlorine is a yellow-green halogen gas with a strong, irritating odor. Discovered by Carl Wilhelm Scheele in 1774, it is a powerful oxidizing agent and highly reactive. Chlorine is best known for its disinfecting properties and is widely used in water treatment to kill harmful bacteria. It is also used in the production of plastics like PVC, and in cleaning agents, solvents, and dyes. Chlorine exists in nature as chloride salts, particularly in seawater. While essential in small amounts, chlorine gas is toxic and was used as a chemical weapon during World War I. Safety precautions are critical in its use.'),(18,'Ar','Argon',39.948,3,18,'p','Noble Gas','Gas',0.001784,83.8,87.3,'[Ne] 3s2 3p6',NULL,'0','Colorless gas','Lord Rayleigh & William Ramsay',1894,0,'Argon is a noble gas that was discovered in 1894 by Lord Rayleigh and William Ramsay. It is the third most abundant gas in Earth?s atmosphere, making up about 0.93%. Argon is chemically inert and does not form stable compounds under normal conditions. Its inertness makes it ideal for use in welding, light bulbs, and scientific research requiring a non-reactive environment. Argon produces a faint violet-blue glow when electrified and is used in some types of lasers. It is also used in double-pane windows to improve insulation. Despite its inactivity, argon plays a vital role in protecting sensitive processes.'),(19,'K','Potassium',39.098,4,1,'s','Alkali Metal','Solid',0.862,336.53,1032,'[Ar] 4s1',0.82,'+1','Silvery gray','Humphry Davy',1807,0,'Potassium is a soft, silvery-white alkali metal that reacts explosively with water. Discovered by Humphry Davy in 1807, potassium is vital to human health, playing a key role in muscle contraction, nerve transmission, and heart function. It is found in bananas, potatoes, and many vegetables. In agriculture, potassium is a key component of fertilizers. It is also used in fireworks, soaps, and glass manufacturing. Because of its high reactivity, potassium must be stored under oil or inert gas. Its compounds, particularly potassium chloride, are used in medicine and food processing. It burns with a violet flame.'),(20,'Ca','Calcium',40.078,4,2,'s','Alkaline Earth Metal','Solid',1.55,1115,1757,'[Ar] 4s2',1,'+2','Dull gray or silvery','Humphry Davy',1808,0,'Calcium is a soft gray alkaline earth metal discovered by Humphry Davy in 1808. It is essential for life, contributing to strong bones and teeth, muscle contraction, and blood clotting. Calcium is the most abundant metal in the human body and is found in dairy products, leafy greens, and fortified foods. In industry, calcium is used in cement, plaster, and construction materials like limestone and marble. It also serves as a reducing agent in metal extraction. Though calcium metal is reactive, especially with water, it is typically encountered in compound form in nature, such as calcium carbonate or gypsum.'),(21,'Sc','Scandium',44.955,4,3,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',2.985,1814,3109,'[Ar] 3d1 4s2',1.36,'+3','Silvery-white','Lars Fredrik Nilson',1879,0,'Scandium is a lightweight transition metal discovered in 1879 by Lars Fredrik Nilson. It was predicted earlier by Mendeleev and called ekaboron. Found in rare minerals like thortveitite, scandium has unique applications in aerospace components and sporting equipment due to its strength and low density. Although relatively scarce, its addition to aluminum alloys significantly enhances performance. Interestingly, its chemistry closely resembles both the lanthanides and aluminum. Scandium also plays a role in high-intensity metal halide lamps. Despite its usefulness, scandium remains expensive due to the difficulty in separating it from ore. Its future potential in advanced materials remains promising.'),(22,'Ti','Titanium',47.867,4,4,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',4.506,1941,3560,'[Ar] 3d2 4s2',1.54,'+3, +4','Silvery gray-white','William Gregor',1791,0,'Titanium is known for its exceptional strength-to-weight ratio and corrosion resistance. Discovered in 1791 by William Gregor, it was later named after the Titans of Greek mythology. Titanium is widely used in aerospace, medical implants, and sporting goods. Despite being the ninth-most abundant element in Earth?s crust, it is challenging to extract. Titanium dioxide, a compound of titanium, is used in sunscreens, paints, and even food coloring. Its non-toxic and biocompatible nature makes it ideal for human implants like joint replacements. This durable metal is also used in high-performance military and industrial equipment, making it a valuable modern material.'),(23,'V','Vanadium',50.942,4,5,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',6.11,2183,3680,'[Ar] 3d3 4s2',1.63,'+2, +3, +4, +5','Silvery-gray','Andrés Manuel del Río',1801,0,'Vanadium is a silvery-gray metal with excellent strength and corrosion resistance. It was first discovered in 1801 by Andrés Manuel del Río but was rediscovered and confirmed by Nils Sefström in 1830. The element is named after the Norse goddess Vanadis, symbolizing its colorful compounds. Vanadium is primarily used to make strong steel alloys and tools. It also plays a key role in redox flow batteries for large-scale energy storage. In small amounts, vanadium is biologically significant for some animals. Its unique ability to exist in multiple oxidation states makes it a fascinating subject in coordination chemistry.'),(24,'Cr','Chromium',51.996,4,6,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',7.19,2180,2944,'[Ar] 3d5 4s1',1.66,'+2, +3, +6','Silvery metallic','Louis Nicolas Vauquelin',1797,0,'Chromium is a hard, lustrous metal known for giving shine and durability to chrome plating. Discovered in 1797 by Louis Nicolas Vauquelin, it was named from the Greek word ?chroma,? meaning color, due to the vibrant colors of its compounds. Chromium is widely used in stainless steel production, corrosion-resistant coatings, and pigments for paints and dyes. Its hexavalent form is toxic and carcinogenic, made famous in the Erin Brockovich case. On the other hand, trivalent chromium is an essential nutrient. Chromium?s vibrant green oxide is used in polishing, and its durability makes it indispensable in modern materials science.'),(25,'Mn','Manganese',54.938,4,7,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',7.21,1519,2334,'[Ar] 3d5 4s2',1.55,'+2, +4, +7','Gray-white','Johan Gottlieb Gahn',1774,0,'Manganese is a versatile element essential for steel production and biological systems. Discovered in 1774 by Johan Gottlieb Gahn, manganese improves the strength and toughness of steel when alloyed. It is also used in dry-cell batteries and pigments. Manganese dioxide is an important industrial catalyst and was one of the first components used in alkaline batteries. In biology, manganese is required for bone development and enzyme activation. Though essential in small amounts, excessive exposure can be toxic. Its rich chemistry and importance in both heavy industry and health make manganese a critical but often overlooked element.'),(26,'Fe','Iron',55.845,4,8,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',7.874,1811,3134,'[Ar] 3d6 4s2',1.83,'+2, +3','Grayish metal','Known since antiquity',NULL,0,'Iron is one of the most historically and economically important elements. Known since antiquity, it is the main component of steel and is used in construction, tools, transportation, and more. Iron is also a key biological element, vital for transporting oxygen in the blood via hemoglobin. Found abundantly in Earth?s crust and core, iron ores like hematite and magnetite are mined globally. Iron rusts easily, forming reddish-brown iron oxide, yet remains indispensable. The Iron Age, named for this element, marked a major technological shift in human history. Its strength, abundance, and utility make it a cornerstone of civilization.'),(27,'Co','Cobalt',58.933,4,9,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',8.86,1768,3200,'[Ar] 3d7 4s2',1.88,'+2, +3','Hard, lustrous, gray','Georg Brandt',1735,0,'Cobalt is a shiny, hard, bluish-gray metal discovered in 1735 by Georg Brandt. It was the first metal discovered by a modern scientist rather than known since ancient times. Cobalt is essential in the manufacture of high-strength alloys and powerful magnets. Its vivid blue salts have been used in pottery and glass for centuries. Cobalt is also a vital trace element in human nutrition, forming the core of vitamin B12. In modern times, cobalt is used in rechargeable batteries and aerospace materials. Its radioactive isotope, cobalt-60, is used in cancer therapy and sterilization processes, making it highly valuable in medicine.'),(28,'Ni','Nickel',58.693,4,10,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',8.908,1728,3186,'[Ar] 3d8 4s2',1.91,'+2, +3','Silvery-white','Axel Fredrik Cronstedt',1751,0,'Nickel is a lustrous, silvery-white metal with excellent corrosion resistance and durability. Discovered by Axel Fredrik Cronstedt in 1751, nickel is extensively used in stainless steel, coins, and batteries. It forms strong alloys and resists oxidation, making it ideal for harsh environments. Found in Earth?s crust and core, nickel is also present in meteorites. Its use in rechargeable batteries has surged due to electric vehicle growth. Interestingly, some plants are capable of accumulating large amounts of nickel and are being studied for phytomining. Though common, nickel?s versatility continues to power new innovations in technology and energy.'),(29,'Cu','Copper',63.546,4,11,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',8.96,1357,2835,'[Ar] 3d10 4s1',1.9,'+1, +2','Reddish-orange','Known since antiquity',NULL,0,'Copper is one of the oldest metals used by humans, known since ancient times for its reddish color and excellent conductivity. Used in coins, wiring, and plumbing, copper?s malleability and resistance to corrosion make it highly versatile. It is essential for electrical infrastructure, renewable energy, and electronics. Copper is also biologically important, playing a role in enzyme function and iron metabolism. Its green patina, seen on the Statue of Liberty, forms from oxidation over time. Alloys like bronze and brass showcase copper?s adaptability. From ancient tools to modern tech, copper continues to be an essential element of human progress.'),(30,'Zn','Zinc',65.38,4,12,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',7.14,693,1180,'[Ar] 3d10 4s2',1.65,'+2','Bluish-silver','Andreas Marggraf',1746,0,'Zinc is a bluish-white metal that resists corrosion and plays a vital role in biology and industry. Discovered in 1746 by Andreas Marggraf, zinc was used long before in ancient India and China. It is crucial for immune function, wound healing, and growth. Zinc is widely used to galvanize steel, preventing rust. It also forms alloys like brass and is used in batteries and paints. Zinc oxide is common in sunscreens, ointments, and rubber manufacturing. Fun fact: zinc burns with a bright green flame. Despite its humble image, zinc is a powerhouse element with countless industrial and biological roles.'),(31,'Ga','Gallium',69.723,4,13,'p','Post-transition Metal','Solid',5.91,302.91,2477,'[Ar] 3d10 4s2 4p1',1.81,'+1, +3','Silvery blue','Lecoq de Boisbaudran',1875,0,'Gallium is a fascinating metal that melts in your hand, as its melting point is just around 30°C. Discovered in 1875 by French chemist Lecoq de Boisbaudran, it was predicted by Mendeleev before it was even found and originally called \"eka-aluminum.\" Gallium plays a major role in electronics, especially in semiconductors like gallium arsenide (GaAs), which is used in LEDs, solar panels, and high-speed electronics. Despite its soft, silvery appearance, gallium expands when it solidifies, which can break containers?making it both unique and a little mischievous. It?s also non-toxic and used in medical thermometers and research.'),(32,'Ge','Germanium',72.63,4,14,'p','Metalloid','Solid',5.323,1211.4,3106,'[Ar] 3d10 4s2 4p2',2.01,'+2, +4','Grayish-white','Clemens Winkler',1886,0,'Germanium is a brittle, gray-white metalloid discovered by Clemens Winkler in 1886. It had been predicted by Mendeleev as \"eka-silicon\" before it was found. Germanium is a crucial component in electronics, especially in fiber optics, infrared optics, and solar cells. It was historically used in the first transistors, making it key to the invention of modern computing. Germanium\'s semi-conducting properties make it indispensable in high-speed circuitry and detectors. Interestingly, it?s also used in polymer production and even in some supplements, though its health benefits are still debated. Germanium remains a quiet hero in technology.'),(33,'As','Arsenic',74.9216,4,15,'p','Metalloid','Solid',5.776,1090,887,'[Ar] 3d10 4s2 4p3',2.18,'-3, +3, +5','Steel gray','Known since ancient times',NULL,1,'Arsenic is a notorious element with a dark history but essential modern applications. Known since ancient times, it has been used as a poison, pigment, and medicine. This gray metalloid is brittle and has three allotropes: gray, yellow, and black. Despite its toxic reputation, arsenic is used in semiconductors, wood preservation, and even cancer treatments in controlled doses. Arsenic trioxide is a powerful chemotherapy agent for leukemia. It?s also found naturally in groundwater in some regions, leading to significant health concerns. The dual nature of arsenic?dangerous and useful?makes it one of the most intriguing elements on the periodic table.'),(34,'Se','Selenium',78.971,4,16,'p','Nonmetal','Solid',4.809,494,958,'[Ar] 3d10 4s2 4p4',2.55,'-2, +4, +6','Red, gray, black','Jöns Jakob Berzelius',1817,0,'Selenium is a nonmetal with properties between sulfur and tellurium. Discovered by Jöns Jakob Berzelius in 1817, it was named after the Greek word \"selene,\" meaning moon. Selenium conducts electricity better in light than in darkness, which made it valuable in early photocopiers and solar cells. It?s essential in small amounts for human health, supporting antioxidant enzymes, but can be toxic in excess. Selenium is also used in glassmaking to remove green tints and in pigments for red-colored paints. Fun fact: some species of bacteria \"breathe\" selenium instead of oxygen in extreme environments!'),(35,'Br','Bromine',79.904,4,17,'p','Halogen','Liquid',3.1028,265.8,332,'[Ar] 3d10 4s2 4p5',2.96,'-1, +1, +5','Reddish-brown liquid','Antoine Balard',1826,1,'Bromine is one of only two elements that are liquid at room temperature, along with mercury. Discovered in 1826 by Antoine Balard, this reddish-brown halogen has a strong, unpleasant smell and is highly reactive. Bromine is used in flame retardants, water purification, and pharmaceuticals. Despite its toxicity, it plays a role in producing certain sedatives and agricultural chemicals. Its volatile nature makes it dangerous to handle without proper precautions. In nature, it?s found mostly as bromide salts in seawater. Bromine?s uniqueness as a reactive liquid gives it a curious position on the periodic table.'),(36,'Kr','Krypton',83.798,4,18,'p','Noble Gas','Gas',0.003733,115.79,119.93,'[Ar] 3d10 4s2 4p6',NULL,'0','Colorless gas','William Ramsay & Morris Travers',1898,0,'Krypton is a colorless, odorless noble gas discovered in 1898 by William Ramsay and Morris Travers. It is incredibly unreactive due to its full outer electron shell, making it chemically inert under most conditions. Krypton is used in certain types of photographic flashes and high-performance lighting, including airport runway lights. It\'s also used in some lasers that cut precision materials. Despite its ghostly name, Krypton isn?t from Superman?s planet, but it does have a ?super? role in science and technology. Its discovery further proved the existence of the noble gases group in the periodic table.'),(37,'Rb','Rubidium',85.4678,5,1,'s','Alkali Metal','Solid',1.532,312.45,961,'[Kr] 5s1',0.82,'+1','Silvery-white metallic','Robert Bunsen & Gustav Kirchhoff',1861,1,'Rubidium is a highly reactive alkali metal, discovered in 1861 by Robert Bunsen and Gustav Kirchhoff using flame spectroscopy. Its name comes from the Latin word \"rubidius,\" meaning deep red, because of its bright red spectral lines. Rubidium reacts violently with water, forming hydrogen gas and heat, often enough to ignite flames. It?s used in research, specialized glasses, and atomic clocks. Rubidium atomic clocks are extremely precise, rivaling cesium clocks. Despite its radioactivity, rubidium occurs naturally in small amounts. A soft, silvery metal, it?s fascinating for scientists and dangerous to handle casually.'),(38,'Sr','Strontium',87.62,5,2,'s','Alkaline Earth Metal','Solid',2.64,1050,1655,'[Kr] 5s2',0.95,'+2','Silvery-white metallic','Adair Crawford',1790,1,'Strontium is an alkaline earth metal that?s best known for its vivid red flame. Discovered in 1790 by Adair Crawford, it was named after the Scottish village of Strontian, where its ore was first identified. Strontium salts are used in fireworks and flares to produce brilliant red colors. Its isotope Sr-90 is radioactive and produced in nuclear fission, used in radioisotope thermoelectric generators. Non-radioactive strontium is used in producing glass for TVs and in bone health supplements. The metal reacts quickly with water and air, so it must be stored carefully. Strontium adds color and caution to the periodic table.'),(39,'Y','Yttrium',88.905,5,3,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',4.472,1526,3338,'[Kr] 4d1 5s2',1.22,'+3','Silvery-white metallic','Johan Gadolin',1794,0,'Yttrium is a transition metal named after the Swedish village of Ytterby, which is also the namesake of several other rare earth elements. Discovered in 1794 by Johan Gadolin, yttrium is used in LEDs, phosphors for TVs, and superconductors. It?s also used in cancer treatment as part of radioactive isotopes. Yttrium adds strength to aluminum and magnesium alloys and plays a role in high-temperature ceramics. Its role in science and technology is ever-growing, from materials engineering to medicine. Though obscure to the general public, yttrium is a workhorse of modern materials.'),(40,'Zr','Zirconium',91.224,5,4,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',6.52,2128,4682,'[Kr] 4d2 5s2',1.33,'+4','Silvery white','Martin Heinrich Klaproth',1789,0,'Zirconium is a corrosion-resistant metal that shines in nuclear reactors and artificial gemstones. Discovered in 1789 by Martin Heinrich Klaproth, it was named after the mineral zircon. Zirconium?s strength and resistance to heat and corrosion make it ideal for nuclear fuel rods. It is also used in surgical instruments and heat-resistant ceramics. In jewelry, zirconia (ZrO?) is a brilliant diamond substitute. Despite being metal, it rarely corrodes and does not absorb neutrons?hence its popularity in reactors. Zirconium combines beauty and brawn in science and style alike.'),(41,'Nb','Niobium',92.906,5,5,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',8.57,2750,5017,'[Kr] 4d4 5s1',1.6,'+3, +5','Gray metallic','Charles Hatchett',1801,0,'Niobium, discovered by Charles Hatchett in 1801, is a soft, gray, ductile transition metal often found with tantalum. It strengthens steel and is used in pipelines, jet engines, and superconducting magnets. It has impressive corrosion resistance, making it useful in chemical equipment. Niobium also finds use in medical implants due to its biocompatibility. One of its fun traits is its ability to form colorful oxides, making it popular in decorative jewelry. Although not widely known to the public, it plays an essential role in modern engineering and infrastructure.'),(42,'Mo','Molybdenum',95.95,5,6,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',10.28,2896,4912,'[Kr] 4d5 5s1',2.16,'+2, +3, +4, +5, +6','Silvery-gray','Carl Wilhelm Scheele',1778,0,'Molybdenum is a strong, silvery metal discovered in 1778 by Carl Wilhelm Scheele. With a very high melting point, it is commonly used in steel alloys to enhance strength and resistance to corrosion. It?s vital in oil refining and aerospace components. In biology, it?s an essential trace element aiding enzymatic activity. Despite being tough, it is softer than tungsten but more versatile in applications. Interestingly, it was once mistaken for lead before its true identity was revealed. Molybdenum is essential both to modern industry and to life.'),(43,'Tc','Technetium',98,5,7,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',11.5,2430,4538,'[Kr] 4d5 5s2',1.9,'+4, +5, +7','Silvery-gray','Carlo Perrier & Emilio Segrè',1937,1,'Technetium, the first man-made element, was discovered in 1937 by Carlo Perrier and Emilio Segrè. It does not occur naturally in significant amounts and all its isotopes are radioactive. It is used in medical imaging, especially in radiopharmaceuticals for diagnosing heart and bone conditions. Technetium is also used to inhibit corrosion in steel. The name derives from the Greek word \"technetos\" meaning artificial. It is one of the few elements created in labs before being found in nature, albeit in trace amounts in stars and uranium ores.'),(44,'Ru','Ruthenium',101.07,5,8,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',12.37,2607,4423,'[Kr] 4d7 5s1',2.2,'+2, +3, +4, +6, +8','Silvery white','Karl Ernst Claus',1844,0,'Ruthenium was discovered in 1844 by Karl Ernst Claus and is named after \"Ruthenia,\" a historical name for Russia. It is a rare transition metal used in electrical contacts, chip resistors, and catalytic converters. Ruthenium also helps harden platinum and palladium in jewelry. In electronics, its compounds improve data storage devices. It is being researched for its anticancer properties and role in solar energy. Despite its obscurity, ruthenium is a silent contributor to many modern technologies and scientific advancements.'),(45,'Rh','Rhodium',102.91,5,9,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',12.41,2237,3968,'[Kr] 4d8 5s1',2.28,'+1, +2, +3, +4, +5','Silvery-white metallic','William Hyde Wollaston',1803,0,'Rhodium is a rare, silvery-white metal discovered by William Hyde Wollaston in 1803. It is extremely reflective and corrosion-resistant, making it ideal for jewelry plating. Rhodium plays a crucial role in catalytic converters by reducing toxic emissions from vehicles. It is also used in electronics and as a catalyst in chemical manufacturing. Despite being one of the rarest elements, rhodium has gained popularity for its brilliance and durability. Its scarcity makes it one of the most valuable metals, often trading at prices higher than gold or platinum.'),(46,'Pd','Palladium',106.42,5,10,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',12.02,1828.05,3236,'[Kr] 4d10',2.2,'+2, +4','Silvery-white','William Hyde Wollaston',1803,0,'Palladium was discovered in 1803 by William Hyde Wollaston and named after the asteroid Pallas. It is a key element in catalytic converters, purifying vehicle exhaust gases. Palladium is also used in electronics, dentistry, and jewelry. Its ability to absorb hydrogen makes it useful in hydrogen storage and purification systems. It is a major component in fuel cell technologies. With a beautiful finish and resistance to tarnish, palladium is often alloyed with gold for white gold jewelry. Its industrial demand makes it one of the most valuable metals on the market.'),(47,'Ag','Silver',107.87,5,11,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',10.49,1234.93,2435,'[Kr] 4d10 5s1',1.93,'+1','Shiny gray-white','Known since ancient times',NULL,0,'Silver, known since ancient times, is prized for its luster and conductivity. It has the highest electrical and thermal conductivity of any element, making it essential in electronics, solar panels, and batteries. Silver also has antimicrobial properties and is used in medical tools, wound dressings, and water filters. Historically, it has been used for coins, jewelry, and art. Though it tarnishes over time, its beauty and utility make silver an enduringly valuable material in both industry and culture.'),(48,'Cd','Cadmium',112.41,5,12,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',8.65,594.22,1040,'[Kr] 4d10 5s2',1.69,'+2','Silvery bluish-gray','Friedrich Stromeyer',1817,1,'Cadmium is a soft, bluish-white metal discovered in 1817 by Friedrich Stromeyer. It?s primarily used in rechargeable batteries, pigments, and coatings. Though toxic, cadmium plays a key role in various industrial processes. Its compounds were once popular in vivid yellow and red pigments. Due to its harmful effects on health and the environment, cadmium usage is now tightly regulated. Despite this, its corrosion resistance and low melting point keep it relevant in electronics and solar panels.'),(49,'In','Indium',114.82,5,13,'p','Post-transition Metal','Solid',7.31,429.75,2345,'[Kr] 4d10 5s2 5p1',1.78,'+1, +3','Silvery white','Ferdinand Reich & Hieronymous Richter',1863,0,'Indium was discovered in 1863 by Reich and Richter through spectroscopic analysis. It is soft enough to be cut with a knife and leaves a high-pitched squeal when bent. Indium is used in LCD screens, touchscreens, solar panels, and solders. The element forms a transparent conductive oxide when combined with tin, known as indium tin oxide (ITO). Despite its relative obscurity, it is essential in electronics. Its name comes from the indigo-blue line seen in its emission spectrum.'),(50,'Sn','Tin',118.71,5,14,'p','Post-transition Metal','Solid',7.265,505.08,2875,'[Kr] 4d10 5s2 5p2',1.96,'+2, +4','Silvery-white','Known since ancient times',NULL,0,'Tin, known since ancient times, was a vital part of the Bronze Age when it was alloyed with copper. Today, it is used in solder, tin plating, and various metal alloys. Tin resists corrosion, making it ideal for food containers. It has two forms: a metallic \"white tin\" and brittle \"gray tin\" that forms at low temperatures ? a phenomenon known as tin pest. Tin also plays a role in organotin compounds for industrial uses. While humble in appearance, tin has been crucial to human progress.'),(51,'Sb','Antimony',121.76,5,15,'p','Metalloid','Solid',6.697,903.78,1860,'[Kr] 4d10 5s2 5p3',2.05,'-3, +3, +5','Silvery lustrous gray','Known since ancient times',NULL,0,'Antimony is a silvery-gray metalloid known since antiquity. Ancient Egyptians used it as kohl eyeliner, and it has been mentioned in texts from over 5000 years ago. It is used in flame retardants, lead-acid batteries, alloys, and semiconductors. Antimony?s brittleness and metallic sheen make it unique among elements. In chemistry, its compounds have diverse industrial applications. Interestingly, it expands upon cooling, making it useful in casting typefaces. Its role in alchemy and early medicine gives it a colorful historical background despite its toxic nature.'),(52,'Te','Tellurium',127.6,5,16,'p','Metalloid','Solid',6.24,722.66,1261,'[Kr] 4d10 5s2 5p4',2.1,'-2, +2, +4, +6','Silvery-white','Franz-Joseph Müller von Reichenstein',1782,0,'Tellurium, discovered in 1782, is a brittle, silvery-white metalloid with a garlic-like odor. It is used in alloys to improve machinability and is vital in the production of thermoelectric devices and solar panels. When burned, tellurium compounds emit a blue flame. Tellurium also enhances the performance of rubber and glass. Although rare, it is found in some gold ores and is often recovered from copper refining. Its unusual properties and ability to form semiconducting compounds make it valuable in high-tech applications.'),(53,'I','Iodine',126.9,5,17,'p','Halogen','Solid',4.933,386.85,457.55,'[Kr] 4d10 5s2 5p5',2.66,'-1, +1, +3, +5, +7','Shiny purple-black crystals','Bernard Courtois',1811,0,'Iodine is a lustrous, purple-black halogen 