m is a soft, silvery metal discovered in 1772 by Carl Wilhelm Scheele. It is highly reactive and oxidizes quickly in air. Barium compounds, especially barium sulfate, are used in medical imaging of the gastrointestinal tract. It is also used in fireworks to produce green flames, and in glassmaking and drilling fluids. Barium is never found free in nature due to its reactivity. Despite its toxicity, controlled use of barium compounds plays an important role in medicine and industry.'),(57,'La','Lanthanum',138.91,6,3,'f','Lanthanide','Solid',6.145,1193,3737,'[Xe] 5d1 6s2',1.1,'+3','Silvery-white','Carl Gustaf Mosander',1839,0,'Lanthanum is a soft, malleable, silvery-white metal discovered in 1839 by Carl Gustaf Mosander. It is the first element in the lanthanide series and is found in rare-earth minerals like monazite. Lanthanum is used in hybrid car batteries, camera lenses, and catalysts for petroleum refining. It improves glass clarity and resistance to alkalis. Though reactive in air, it forms a protective oxide layer. Lanthanum?s versatile chemical behavior makes it valuable in both electronics and optics.'),(58,'Ce','Cerium',140.12,6,NULL,'f','Lanthanide','Solid',6.77,1068,3716,'[Xe] 4f1 5d1 6s2',1.12,'+3, +4','Silvery-white','Martin Heinrich Klaproth & Jöns Jacob Berzelius',1803,0,'Cerium, discovered in 1803, is the most abundant of the rare-earth elements. It is soft, silvery-white, and tarnishes in air. Cerium is used in catalytic converters, glass polishing powders, and lighter flints. It can also absorb gases, making it useful in vacuum tubes. Cerium oxide nanoparticles are being explored in medicine for antioxidant applications. It?s named after the dwarf planet Ceres. Cerium?s unique ability to switch oxidation states makes it useful in redox reactions and industrial catalysis.'),(59,'Pr','Praseodymium',140.91,6,NULL,'f','Lanthanide','Solid',6.77,1208,3793,'[Xe] 4f3 6s2',1.13,'+3','Silvery white','Carl Auer von Welsbach',1885,0,'Praseodymium, discovered in 1885 by Carl Auer von Welsbach, is a soft, silvery lanthanide named from the Greek for \"green twin\" due to its green salts. It is used in aircraft engines, studio lighting, and coloring glass and ceramics. Praseodymium is also used in strong magnets and as an alloy with magnesium in high-strength metals. It helps create yellow-green colors in glasses and enamels and can filter infrared light. Its versatile properties make it valuable in both aesthetic and industrial applications.'),(60,'Nd','Neodymium',144.24,6,NULL,'f','Lanthanide','Solid',7.01,1294,3347,'[Xe] 4f4 6s2',1.14,'+3','Silvery white','Carl Auer von Welsbach',1885,0,'Neodymium, another discovery by Carl Auer von Welsbach in 1885, is a rare-earth metal known for its powerful magnets. Neodymium magnets are the strongest permanent magnets and are used in hard drives, headphones, motors, and wind turbines. It also colors glass in beautiful purples and is used in laser technologies. Though it oxidizes quickly, its magnetic power is unmatched in small sizes. Neodymium?s role in green energy technologies makes it critical to the future of sustainable power.'),(71,'Lu','Lutetium',174.97,6,NULL,'f','Lanthanide','Solid',9.84,1925,3675,'[Xe] 4f14 5d1 6s2',1.27,'+3','Silvery white','Georges Urbain',1907,0,'Lutetium is the last element in the lanthanide series and was discovered independently by Georges Urbain in 1907. It is a silvery-white metal that is relatively stable in air, making it one of the least reactive lanthanides. Lutetium has applications in catalysts used in petroleum refining and in certain cancer treatment therapies using lutetium-based isotopes. Due to its high density and stability, it is also used in some nuclear and electronic applications. Despite being rare and expensive, its unique characteristics make it valuable in scientific and industrial research.'),(72,'Hf','Hafnium',178.49,6,4,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',13.31,2506,4876,'[Xe] 4f14 5d2 6s2',1.3,'+4','Silvery gray','Dirk Coster and Georg von Hevesy',1923,0,'Hafnium is a transition metal known for its excellent corrosion resistance and high melting point. It was discovered in 1923 in Copenhagen, hence its name derived from \"Hafnia,\" the Latin name for the city. Hafnium is chemically similar to zirconium and often occurs with it in mineral deposits. It is widely used in control rods for nuclear reactors because of its ability to absorb neutrons. Additionally, hafnium plays a role in high-temperature ceramics and microprocessor technology due to its thermal stability.'),(73,'Ta','Tantalum',180.95,6,5,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',16.69,3290,5731,'[Xe] 4f14 5d3 6s2',1.5,'+5','Gray blue','Anders Ekeberg',1802,0,'Tantalum is a rare, hard, blue-gray metal known for its exceptional resistance to corrosion. It was discovered by Swedish chemist Anders Ekeberg in 1802. Tantalum is primarily used in electronic components like capacitors and high-power resistors, especially in smartphones, laptops, and other compact devices. Its biocompatibility also makes it useful in surgical implants. Tantalum?s name is derived from the mythological figure Tantalus because of its resistance to absorbing acid, much like the character who could not drink water.'),(74,'W','Tungsten',183.84,6,6,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',19.25,3695,5828,'[Xe] 4f14 5d4 6s2',2.36,'+6, +4','Grayish white','Juan José Elhuyar and Fausto Elhuyar',1783,0,'Tungsten, also known as wolfram, has the highest melting point of all metals and is extremely dense. Discovered in 1783 by the Elhuyar brothers, it is used in applications requiring high temperature resistance, such as light bulb filaments, rocket engine nozzles, and cutting tools. Tungsten is also employed in military armor and radiation shielding. Its symbol \"W\" is derived from its German name \"Wolfram.\" Tungsten?s incredible strength and durability make it one of the most valuable industrial metals today.'),(75,'Re','Rhenium',186.21,6,7,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',21.02,3459,5869,'[Xe] 4f14 5d5 6s2',1.9,'+7, +6, +4','Silvery gray','Ida Noddack, Walter Noddack, and Otto Berg',1925,0,'Rhenium is a rare transition metal that ranks among the highest in melting points and density. It was discovered in 1925 by German scientists Ida and Walter Noddack and Otto Berg. Rhenium is primarily used in high-temperature superalloys for jet engines and in catalysts for refining petroleum. Its rarity makes it expensive, but its strength at extreme temperatures makes it indispensable in aerospace and military technologies. Rhenium is named after the Rhine River, reflecting the site of its discovery.'),(76,'Os','Osmium',190.23,6,8,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',22.59,3306,5285,'[Xe] 4f14 5d6 6s2',2.2,'+4, +6, +8','Bluish-silver','Smithson Tennant',1803,0,'Osmium is the densest naturally occurring element and was discovered in 1803 by British chemist Smithson Tennant. It is a hard, brittle, bluish-white metal that is highly resistant to wear and corrosion. Osmium is used in fountain pen nibs, electrical contacts, and other applications requiring extreme durability. Although it forms a toxic compound, osmium tetroxide, the pure metal is safe in solid form. Osmium?s remarkable density and durability make it a prized material for specialized scientific and industrial uses.'),(77,'Ir','Iridium',192.22,6,9,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',22.56,2719,4701,'[Xe] 4f14 5d7 6s2',2.2,'+3, +4','Silvery white','Smithson Tennant',1803,0,'Iridium is one of the most corrosion-resistant elements known. It was discovered in 1803 by Smithson Tennant during his analysis of platinum ores. Iridium is dense, hard, and brittle, with a bright silvery-white appearance. It is used in spark plugs, crucibles, and scientific equipment exposed to extreme environments. Due to its stability, it is also part of the international standard kilogram prototype. The name ?iridium? comes from the Latin word for rainbow, \"iris\", due to the colorful nature of its salts.'),(78,'Pt','Platinum',195.08,6,10,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',21.45,2041.4,4098,'[Xe] 4f14 5d9 6s1',2.28,'+2, +4','Silvery white','Antonio de Ulloa',1735,0,'Platinum is a precious metal known for its resistance to corrosion and excellent conductivity. It was discovered in South America by Spanish explorer Antonio de Ulloa in 1735. Platinum is used in jewelry, automotive catalytic converters, electrical contacts, and even chemotherapy drugs. It is also essential in fuel cell technology. The name \"platinum\" comes from the Spanish \"platina,\" meaning \"little silver.\" Its durability and rarity have made it a symbol of prestige and value throughout history.'),(79,'Au','Gold',196.97,6,11,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',19.32,1337.33,3129,'[Xe] 4f14 5d10 6s1',2.54,'+1, +3','Metallic yellow','Known since ancient times',NULL,0,'Gold is one of the earliest metals known to humanity, valued for its beauty, rarity, and durability. It has been used for coinage, jewelry, and art since ancient civilizations like Egypt and Mesopotamia. Gold does not tarnish or corrode, making it ideal for long-lasting ornaments and investments. Its conductivity also makes it valuable in electronics. Symbolized by \"Au\" from the Latin \"aurum,\" gold remains a global standard of wealth and economic security. Its allure is truly timeless.'),(80,'Hg','Mercury',200.59,6,12,'d','Transition Metal','Liquid',13.534,234.32,629.88,'[Xe] 4f14 5d10 6s2',2,'+1, +2','Silvery liquid','Known since ancient times',NULL,1,'Mercury is the only metal that is liquid at standard temperature and pressure. Known since ancient times, it was used in thermometers, barometers, and alchemical practices. Its Latin name \"hydrargyrum\" means \"liquid silver,\" which is reflected in its symbol \"Hg.\" Although fascinating, mercury is toxic, and its use has been reduced in recent years. It forms alloys with other metals, called amalgams, and has been used in gold mining and dental fillings. Mercury?s unique liquid state continues to captivate scientists and historians alike.'),(81,'Tl','Thallium',204.38,6,13,'p','Post-transition Metal','Solid',11.85,577,1746,'[Xe] 4f14 5d10 6s2 6p1',1.62,'+1, +3','Silvery white','William Crookes',1861,0,'Thallium is a soft, bluish-gray metal that tarnishes quickly in air. Discovered in 1861 by William Crookes using flame spectroscopy, it was named after the Greek word \"thallos,\" meaning green shoot. Highly toxic, thallium was once used in rat poison and insecticides. Today, it finds niche uses in electronics, infrared optics, and low-temperature thermometers. Despite its danger, thallium compounds have helped scientists study neurological functions. Its softness and malleability are similar to lead, but it reacts more readily with oxygen and water vapor, forming a dull oxide layer.'),(82,'Pb','Lead',207.2,6,14,'p','Post-transition Metal','Solid',11.34,600.6,2022,'[Xe] 4f14 5d10 6s2 6p2',2.33,'+2, +4','Dull gray','Known since ancient times',NULL,0,'Lead is one of the first metals used by humans, dating back thousands of years. Known for its malleability, density, and corrosion resistance, it was widely used in pipes, paints, and even cosmetics in ancient Rome. Its symbol, Pb, derives from the Latin word \"plumbum.\" Due to its toxicity, especially to children, its use is now heavily restricted. Lead is still used in car batteries, radiation shielding, and some glassware. A fun fact: the phrase \"piping hot\" may stem from Roman use of lead pipes in heating systems.'),(83,'Bi','Bismuth',208.98,6,15,'p','Post-transition Metal','Solid',9.78,544.7,1837,'[Xe] 4f14 5d10 6s2 6p3',2.02,'+3, +5','Silvery with pink hue','Known since ancient times',NULL,0,'Bismuth is a brittle, silvery metal with a pinkish hue. Known since ancient times, it was often confused with lead and tin. Today, bismuth is valued for its low toxicity, making it a safe substitute for lead in various applications. It is used in cosmetics, pharmaceuticals like Pepto-Bismol, and fire detection systems. A fun fact is that bismuth expands as it solidifies, which is quite rare for metals. It also forms beautiful, iridescent crystals with stair-step structures, popular among collectors.'),(84,'Po','Polonium',209,6,16,'p','Post-transition Metal','Solid',9.2,527,1235,'[Xe] 4f14 5d10 6s2 6p4',2,'+2, +4','Silvery','Marie Curie',1898,1,'Polonium is a rare and highly radioactive metal discovered by Marie Curie in 1898. Named after her homeland, Poland, polonium was the first element discovered through radioactivity. It emits alpha particles and is extremely toxic, even in microscopic quantities. Despite its danger, it has been used in anti-static devices and nuclear applications. In 2006, it made headlines as the poison used in the assassination of a former Russian spy. Polonium?s intense radioactivity makes it glow faintly blue in the dark.'),(85,'At','Astatine',210,6,17,'p','Metalloid','Solid',7,575,610,'[Xe] 4f14 5d10 6s2 6p5',2.2,'-1, +1, +3, +5, +7','Unknown, likely metallic','Corson, MacKenzie, Segrè',1940,1,'Astatine is the rarest naturally occurring element on Earth. It was first synthesized in 1940 by Corson, MacKenzie, and Segrè. Belonging to the halogen group, astatine shares properties with iodine and bromine. Due to its extreme scarcity and short half-life, it remains one of the least studied elements. Scientists estimate that only a few grams exist on Earth at any given time. Its name comes from the Greek \"astatos,\" meaning unstable. There is ongoing research into its potential in cancer treatments through targeted radiotherapy.'),(86,'Rn','Radon',222,6,18,'p','Noble Gas','Gas',0.00973,202,211.3,'[Xe] 4f14 5d10 6s2 6p6',NULL,'0','Colorless gas','Friedrich Ernst Dorn',1900,1,'Radon is a colorless, odorless, radioactive noble gas discovered by Friedrich Ernst Dorn in 1900. It forms naturally as uranium decays in soil and rock. Radon can seep into homes, especially in basements, and prolonged exposure can cause lung cancer. In fact, it is the second leading cause of lung cancer after smoking. Despite its danger, radon has been used in some forms of cancer treatment. Fun fact: radon was once called \"emanation\" due to its ability to escape from radium.'),(87,'Fr','Francium',223,7,1,'s','Alkali Metal','Solid',1.87,300,950,'[Rn] 7s1',0.7,'+1','Unknown','Marguerite Perey',1939,1,'Francium is a highly radioactive and extremely rare alkali metal. Discovered in 1939 by Marguerite Perey in France, it was the last element discovered in nature. Francium exists only in trace amounts in uranium ores and decays rapidly, with a half-life of just 22 minutes. Due to its instability, it has no practical uses and has only been studied in small quantities under special conditions. It is named after France and is the second rarest naturally occurring element after astatine.'),(88,'Ra','Radium',226,7,2,'s','Alkaline Earth Metal','Solid',5.5,973,2010,'[Rn] 7s2',0.9,'+2','Silvery white','Marie Curie',1898,1,'Radium is a radioactive metal discovered by Marie and Pierre Curie in 1898 while researching pitchblende. It was once used in luminous paints for watches and instrument dials due to its ability to glow in the dark. However, the health hazards of radium exposure became tragically evident with the \"Radium Girls\" in the 1920s. Today, radium is used only in limited medical applications. It decays into radon gas and emits strong radiation, making it a subject of ongoing scientific interest.'),(89,'Ac','Actinium',227,7,3,'f','Actinide','Solid',10.07,1500,3500,'[Rn] 6d1 7s2',1.1,'+3','Silvery white','Friedrich Oskar Giesel',1899,1,'Actinium is a soft, silvery-white metal and marks the beginning of the actinide series. Discovered in 1899 by Friedrich Giesel, it is highly radioactive and glows blue in the dark due to its intense radioactivity. Actinium was used in early cancer treatments and continues to be explored in radiation therapy. It occurs naturally in trace amounts in uranium ores. Although not widely used commercially, it serves as a neutron source when combined with beryllium.'),(90,'Th','Thorium',232.04,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',11.72,2023,5061,'[Rn] 6d2 7s2',1.3,'+4','Silvery','Jöns Jakob Berzelius',1828,1,'Thorium is a slightly radioactive, silvery metal discovered in 1828 by Swedish chemist Jöns Jakob Berzelius. Named after Thor, the Norse god of thunder, thorium is more abundant than uranium and has been proposed as a cleaner alternative for nuclear power. It is found in minerals like monazite and has been used in gas mantles for lanterns. Thorium reactors promise high efficiency and safety, sparking renewed interest in the element. A cool fact: thorium can potentially reduce nuclear waste in future reactors.'),(91,'Pa','Protactinium',231.04,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',15.37,1841,4300,'[Rn] 5f2 6d1 7s2',1.5,'+5, +4','Silvery gray','Kasper Fajans and Oswald Helmuth Göhring',1913,1,'Protactinium is a dense, silvery-gray actinide metal discovered in 1913. It was named for being the precursor to actinium in the radioactive decay series. Highly radioactive and toxic, protactinium is found in trace amounts in uranium ores and has few applications outside of scientific research. Due to its scarcity and difficulty in handling, it is one of the rarest and most expensive naturally occurring elements. Despite its limited use, its complex electron structure provides insight into nuclear physics and the behavior of heavy elements.'),(92,'U','Uranium',238.03,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',18.95,1405.3,4404,'[Rn] 5f3 6d1 7s2',1.38,'+6, +5, +4, +3','Silvery gray','Martin Heinrich Klaproth',1789,1,'Uranium is a heavy, silvery-white metal discovered in 1789 by German chemist Martin Klaproth. Named after the planet Uranus, it is weakly radioactive and naturally occurs in several isotopes, the most important being U-235 and U-238. Uranium is widely used as fuel in nuclear reactors and weapons. Its discovery marked the beginning of modern nuclear science. A fun fact: uranium glass was once popular for its yellow-green color and glows under UV light. Despite its radioactivity, it remains one of the most studied elements in nuclear chemistry.'),(93,'Np','Neptunium',237,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',20.45,917,4273,'[Rn] 5f4 6d1 7s2',1.36,'+5, +4, +3','Silvery metallic','Edwin McMillan and Philip Abelson',1940,1,'Neptunium is the first transuranic element, discovered in 1940 by Edwin McMillan and Philip Abelson. It was named after Neptune, the planet following Uranus, mirroring its position after uranium. Neptunium is radioactive and found in small amounts in uranium ores or produced in nuclear reactors. It has potential use in nuclear batteries and weapons, though it is mainly used for scientific research. One unique trait is its multiple oxidation states, making it interesting for chemists studying actinide behavior.'),(94,'Pu','Plutonium',244,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',19.86,912.5,3505,'[Rn] 5f6 7s2',1.28,'+4, +5, +6, +7, +3','Silvery gray','Glenn T. Seaborg et al.',1940,1,'Plutonium is a heavy, radioactive metal discovered in 1940 by Glenn T. Seaborg and colleagues. Named after the dwarf planet Pluto, it is best known for its use in nuclear weapons and reactors. Plutonium-239 is fissile and was a key component of the atomic bomb dropped on Nagasaki. Although highly toxic, it also powers space missions through radioisotope thermoelectric generators (RTGs). It oxidizes quickly in air, forming a dull coating. Fun fact: plutonium can spontaneously ignite in dry air when finely divided.'),(95,'Am','Americium',243,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',12,1449,2880,'[Rn] 5f7 7s2',1.3,'+3, +4, +5, +6','Silvery white','Glenn T. Seaborg et al.',1944,1,'Americium was discovered in 1944 as part of the Manhattan Project and named after the Americas, following the naming pattern of europium. It is a synthetic element and doesn?t occur naturally. Americium-241 is commonly used in smoke detectors due to its ability to emit alpha particles. It also has uses in industrial gauges and research. Although highly radioactive and toxic, it has become an important tool in daily life. Its presence in every modern smoke detector might just be the most widespread use of an actinide.'),(96,'Cm','Curium',247,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',13.51,1613,3383,'[Rn] 5f7 6d1 7s2',1.3,'+3, +4','Silvery metallic','Glenn T. Seaborg, Ralph A. James, and Albert Ghiorso',1944,1,'Curium, named in honor of Marie and Pierre Curie, was discovered in 1944 during World War II. It is a synthetic, radioactive metal with silvery appearance and is highly unstable. Its most notable isotopes, such as Curium-244, are used in space missions as a power source through RTGs. Curium emits intense alpha radiation and glows in the dark due to ionization of air. It has no commercial uses outside of scientific research but plays a vital role in understanding actinide chemistry.'),(97,'Bk','Berkelium',247,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',14.79,1259,2900,'[Rn] 5f9 7s2',1.3,'+3, +4','Silvery','Glenn T. Seaborg et al.',1949,1,'Berkelium was synthesized in 1949 at the University of California, Berkeley, and named after the city. It is a soft, radioactive metal in the actinide series. Produced by bombarding americium with alpha particles, berkelium has no practical uses outside nuclear research. Its synthesis helped pave the way for the discovery of heavier elements like californium. Berkelium?s chemistry helps scientists understand the behavior of transuranic elements and the limits of the periodic table.'),(98,'Cf','Californium',251,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',15.1,1173,1743,'[Rn] 5f10 7s2',1.3,'+3','Silvery','Glenn T. Seaborg et al.',1950,1,'Californium, discovered in 1950, is a radioactive actinide named after California. It was produced by bombarding curium with alpha particles. Californium-252 is a powerful neutron emitter used in neutron moisture gauges, well logging, and cancer treatment. Despite its dangers, it is incredibly useful in initiating nuclear reactors and detecting gold and silver ores. A fun fact: californium is so radioactive that just a microgram can release over 100 million neutrons per second!'),(99,'Es','Einsteinium',252,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',8.84,1133,1269,'[Rn] 5f11 7s2',1.3,'+3','Silvery metallic','Albert Ghiorso et al.',1952,1,'Einsteinium was discovered in 1952 in the debris of the first hydrogen bomb test. Named in honor of Albert Einstein, it is a synthetic and highly radioactive metal. It is produced in minute quantities in nuclear reactors or during nuclear explosions. Because of its scarcity, einsteinium is used only in scientific research. It helped in the discovery of element 100, fermium. Despite being named after a genius, this element remains elusive and mysterious due to its short half-life and limited availability.'),(100,'Fm','Fermium',257,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',NULL,1800,2300,'[Rn] 5f12 7s2',1.3,'+3','Unknown','Albert Ghiorso et al.',1952,1,'Fermium was discovered alongside einsteinium in the fallout of the first hydrogen bomb explosion in 1952. Named after physicist Enrico Fermi, it is a synthetic, highly radioactive actinide. Fermium does not occur naturally and is produced in nuclear reactors or through high-energy particle bombardment. Its most stable isotope, Fm-257, has a half-life of about 100 days. Due to its intense radioactivity and difficulty of production, fermium has no commercial applications and is primarily used for research in nuclear science and the limits of the periodic table.'),(101,'Md','Mendelevium',258,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',NULL,1100,1800,'[Rn] 5f13 7s2',1.3,'+2, +3','Unknown','Albert Ghiorso et al.',1955,1,'Mendelevium is a synthetic radioactive metal discovered in 1955 by a team led by Albert Ghiorso. It was named in honor of Dmitri Mendeleev, the creator of the periodic table. Created by bombarding einsteinium with alpha particles, mendelevium does not occur naturally. It is difficult to produce and available only in minuscule quantities. Its most stable isotope, Md-258, has a half-life of under two months. Because of its rarity and instability, it has no commercial applications and is used only for scientific research, especially in understanding the behavior of heavy actinides.'),(102,'No','Nobelium',259,7,NULL,'f','Actinide','Solid',9.9,1100,1800,'[Rn] 5f14 7s2',1.3,'+2, +3','Unknown','Joint Institute for Nuclear Research',1958,1,'Nobelium is a synthetic radioactive element named after Alfred Nobel, the inventor of dynamite and founder of the Nobel Prizes. First conclusively identified in 1958, its discovery was claimed by multiple laboratories before being settled. Nobelium is created by bombarding curium with carbon ions and exists only in trace amounts. It has several isotopes, with No-259 being one of the most stable. Nobelium exhibits interesting chemical behavior, preferring the +2 oxidation state unlike most other actinides. It?s primarily used in research into actinide chemistry and nuclear science.'),(103,'Lr','Lawrencium',266,7,3,'d','Actinide','Solid',15.6,1900,2600,'[Rn] 5f14 6d1 7s2',1.3,'+3','Unknown','Albert Ghiorso et al.',1961,1,'Lawrencium is the last element in the actinide series and was discovered in 1961 by Albert Ghiorso and his team. It is named after Ernest O. Lawrence, inventor of the cyclotron. Lawrencium is a synthetic element produced in particle accelerators by bombarding californium with boron ions. Due to its high radioactivity and short half-life, lawrencium has no practical applications and is studied solely for research. It?s interesting for chemists because it marks the transition point between the actinides and the transactinides. Its electronic configuration has been debated, reflecting its complex quantum behavior.'),(104,'Rf','Rutherfordium',267,7,4,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',23.2,2100,5500,'[Rn] 5f14 6d2 7s2',NULL,'+4','Unknown','Joint Institute for Nuclear Research',1969,1,'Rutherfordium is a synthetic element first discovered in the 1960s and named in honor of physicist Ernest Rutherford. It was the subject of a naming controversy between Russian and American scientists, but the name Rutherfordium was eventually adopted internationally. Created by bombarding californium or plutonium with light ions, it is a transactinide and part of group 4 of the periodic table. Its chemistry is still being studied, but it behaves similarly to hafnium and zirconium. Rutherfordium has no known practical applications and exists only in laboratory environments.'),(105,'Db','Dubnium',268,7,5,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',29.3,2150,5500,'[Rn] 5f14 6d3 7s2',NULL,'+5','Unknown','Joint Institute for Nuclear Research and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory',1967,1,'Dubnium is a synthetic element discovered independently by teams in Russia and the USA during the late 1960s. It is named after Dubna, Russia, where one of the laboratories is located. Dubnium belongs to group 5 of the periodic table and is part of the transactinide series. Because it is highly unstable and produced in atom-by-atom amounts, dubnium has no commercial uses. Its short-lived isotopes and elusive nature make it a subject of advanced nuclear and theoretical chemistry research.'),(106,'Sg','Seaborgium',269,7,6,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',35,2100,5100,'[Rn] 5f14 6d4 7s2',NULL,'+6','Unknown','Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory',1974,1,'Seaborgium was first synthesized in 1974 and named after Glenn T. Seaborg, a Nobel-winning chemist who contributed to the discovery of many actinides. This naming was controversial as it was the first time an element was named after a living person. Seaborgium is produced by bombarding californium or lead with heavy ions. It is a group 6 transition metal and shares properties with tungsten. Due to its short half-life and radioactivity, seaborgium has no applications outside scientific experiments focused on the behavior of superheavy elements.'),(107,'Bh','Bohrium',270,7,7,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',37.1,2000,5000,'[Rn] 5f14 6d5 7s2',NULL,'+7','Unknown','Gesellschaft für Schwerionenforschung (GSI)',1981,1,'Bohrium is a synthetic element first identified in 1981 by German scientists at the GSI Helmholtz Centre. Named in honor of Niels Bohr, the Danish physicist, it belongs to group 7 in the periodic table and is expected to behave similarly to rhenium. Like other superheavy elements, bohrium is highly unstable, with a very short half-life. Its isotopes are produced in particle accelerators. Because it decays so rapidly, bohrium has no practical applications, but it remains valuable for theoretical research in chemistry and physics.'),(108,'Hs','Hassium',277,7,8,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',41,1600,3100,'[Rn] 5f14 6d6 7s2',NULL,'+8','Unknown','Gesellschaft für Schwerionenforschung (GSI)',1984,1,'Hassium was discovered in 1984 in Germany and named after the German state of Hesse. It is a synthetic and highly radioactive transition metal in group 8. Hassium is produced by bombarding lead with iron nuclei and only a few atoms have ever been observed. It is predicted to be a heavier analog of osmium, possibly showing similar chemical behavior. Due to its instability, hassium is used exclusively in nuclear research, and its discovery helped confirm the stability trends predicted by the periodic table for heavy elements.'),(109,'Mt','Meitnerium',278,7,9,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',37.4,1100,2500,'[Rn] 5f14 6d7 7s2',NULL,'+9','Unknown','Gesellschaft für Schwerionenforschung (GSI)',1982,1,'Meitnerium is a synthetic element named in honor of Lise Meitner, an Austrian-Swedish physicist who contributed to the discovery of nuclear fission. It was first synthesized in 1982 by German researchers at GSI. Meitnerium belongs to group 9 and is expected to behave like iridium. Its most stable isotope, Mt-278, has a half-life of only seconds. Because of its extremely limited production and rapid decay, it has no practical uses, but it stands as a tribute to Meitner?s scientific legacy and role in advancing nuclear physics.'),(110,'Ds','Darmstadtium',281,7,10,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',34.8,1100,1800,'[Rn] 5f14 6d9 7s1',NULL,'+10','Unknown','Gesellschaft für Schwerionenforschung (GSI)',1994,1,'Darmstadtium was first synthesized in 1994 by a team at the GSI Helmholtz Centre for Heavy Ion Research in Darmstadt, Germany. Named after the city of its discovery, darmstadtium is a synthetic, superheavy element in group 10. It is produced by bombarding lead with nickel ions. Its half-life is extremely short, with most isotopes decaying in milliseconds. While no practical uses exist due to its instability, darmstadtium helps scientists understand the properties and possible stability of heavy elements near the \"island of stability.\"'),(111,'Rg','Roentgenium',282,7,11,'d','Transition Metal','Solid',28.7,1100,1700,'[Rn] 5f14 6d10 7s1',NULL,'+1, +3','Unknown','Gesellschaft für Schwerionenforschung (GSI)',1994,1,'Roentgenium is a synthetic element named in honor of Wilhelm Röntgen, the discoverer of X-rays. First synthesized in 1994 by German researchers at GSI, it is an extremely unstable and rare element. Belonging to group 11, it is expected to behave similarly to gold and silver. Due to its fleeting existence?most isotopes have half-lives of milliseconds?roentgenium has no practical applications. It is produced in atom-scale amounts through heavy ion collisions, and its study provides insight into the behavior and structure of superheavy elements.'),(112,'Cn','Copernicium',285,7,12,'d','Transition Metal','Gas',14,1100,1260,'[Rn] 5f14 6d10 7s2',NULL,'+2, +4','Unknown','Gesellschaft für Schwerionenforschung (GSI)',1996,1,'Copernicium was first synthesized in 1996 and named after the astronomer Nicolaus Copernicus. It belongs to group 12 and is a superheavy transition metal. Interestingly, it is predicted to be a volatile gas at room temperature, unlike its metallic group members such as zinc, cadmium, and mercury. Copernicium has very short-lived isotopes, making it difficult to study. The chemical properties are still largely theoretical, and its behavior challenges established trends in the periodic table. It represents a frontier in experimental chemistry.'),(113,'Nh','Nihonium',286,7,13,'p','Post-Transition Metal','Solid',16,700,1430,'[Rn] 5f14 6d10 7s2 7p1',NULL,'+1, +3','Unknown','RIKEN (Japan)',2003,1,'Nihonium is a synthetic element named after \"Nihon,\" one of the Japanese names for Japan. It was officially credited to the RIKEN institute in Japan in 2003, marking the first element discovered by Asian researchers. As a group 13 element, it?s predicted to behave similarly to thallium but with relativistic effects impacting its properties. Only a few atoms have been produced through collisions involving bismuth and zinc. Its discovery not only expanded the periodic table but also highlighted international collaboration in nuclear chemistry.'),(114,'Fl','Flerovium',289,7,14,'p','Post-Transition Metal','Solid',14,600,1400,'[Rn] 5f14 6d10 7s2 7p2',NULL,'+2, +4','Unknown','Joint Institute for Nuclear Research',1999,1,'Flerovium is a synthetic element named after the Flerov Laboratory of Nuclear Reactions in Russia. First synthesized in 1999, it belongs to group 14 and is a possible heavy analog of lead. Flerovium may have unusual properties due to relativistic effects, potentially making it more inert than expected. Its short half-life limits research, but the element remains important for studying the stability of superheavy elements. Its production involved bombarding plutonium with calcium ions.'),(115,'Mc','Moscovium',290,7,15,'p','Post-Transition Metal','Solid',13.5,670,1400,'[Rn] 5f14 6d10 7s2 7p3',NULL,'+1, +3','Unknown','Joint Institute for Nuclear Research and Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory',2003,1,'Moscovium is a superheavy synthetic element named after Moscow Oblast, home to the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research. It was discovered in 2003 in collaboration with American scientists. As a member of group 15, it?s expected to show some similarities to bismuth. Moscovium is produced by bombarding americium with calcium ions. Its short half-life and low production rates limit its study, but it is of great interest in exploring the edge of the periodic table and the potential island of stability.'),(116,'Lv','Livermorium',293,7,16,'p','Post-Transition Metal','Solid',12.9,700,1100,'[Rn] 5f14 6d10 7s2 7p4',NULL,'+2, +4','Unknown','Joint Institute for Nuclear Research and Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory',2000,1,'Livermorium is named in honor of the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, which collaborated with Russian scientists in its discovery in 2000. It belongs to group 16 and is a heavy counterpart to polonium. Livermorium is properties remain largely theoretical due to the extremely short half-life of its isotopes. It was synthesized by bombarding curium with calcium. Studying livermorium helps scientists understand the behavior and chemistry of heavy post-transition metals and supports research into nuclear stability.'),(117,'Ts','Tennessine',294,7,17,'p','Halogen','Solid',7.2,723,883,'[Rn] 5f14 6d10 7s2 7p5',NULL,'-1, +1, +3, +5','Unknown','Oak Ridge National Laboratory, JINR, LLNL',2010,1,'Tennessine, a synthetic element named after the state of Tennessee, was first synthesized in 2010 through international collaboration. It is part of group 17, making it a member of the halogen family. However, its properties may differ significantly due to its high atomic number and resulting relativistic effects. Tennessine was created by bombarding berkelium with calcium. It is highly unstable and exists only for fractions of a second, yet provides valuable insights into the structure and behavior of superheavy elements.'),(118,'Og','Oganesson',294,7,18,'p','Noble Gas','Gas',4.9,325,450,'[Rn] 5f14 6d10 7s2 7p6',NULL,'0, +2, +4','Unknown','Joint Institute for Nuclear Research and Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory',2002,1,'Oganesson is the last known element on the periodic table, named in honor of Russian physicist Yuri Oganessian. It was first synthesized in 2002 and officially confirmed in later years. As a noble gas, it sits in group 18 but behaves very differently from lighter noble gases. Theoretical models suggest oganesson could be reactive and may even exist as a solid under standard conditions. Its extremely short half-life and unique electronic structure make it a focus of cutting-edge nuclear and quantum chemistry research.');
